Abstract

This notebook studies macroeconomic drivers of the Consumer Price Index (CPI) using a multiple linear regression framework. We explore co-movement, test for stationarity and multicollinearity, run OLS models (full and reduced), evaluate diagnostics, and produce a short-range baseline forecast. The goal is to provide clear descriptive and inferential evidence while highlighting limitations from time-series features and proposing robust alternatives.

INTRODUCTION

Inflation affects purchasing power, monetary policy, and household welfare. Understanding which macro variables co-move with CPI helps inform policy and forecasting. This analysis focuses on a set of candidate predictors mortgage rates, unemployment, equity market indices (NASDAQ), disposable income, personal consumption, and household savings and evaluates their statistical association with CPI over the sample period. We emphasize descriptive diagnostics, robust inference, and time-series considerations before making policy statements.

METHODOLOGY

  • Dataset file: US_macroeconomics.csv
  • Data type: Time-series
  • Frequency & sample: Monthly observations from 1980 to 2022 confirm by inspecting df.index and df.head().
  • Variables used:
    • CPI: Consumer Price Index (dependent variable).
    • Mortgage: Mortgage rate (percent or basis points).
    • Unemp_ra: Unemployment rate (percent).
    • NASDAQ: NASDAQ index level.
    • disposable: Disposable personal income.
    • Personal: Personal consumption expenditures.
    • personal_savings: Personal saving metric (units as in CSV).
  • Notes on units & transforms: Many variables are nominal-level series with strong trends; using levels can induce spurious correlations. We will consider log/difference transforms and standardization where appropriate.
  • Missing data & cleaning: Any NA counts are checked and decided on imputation or sample restriction based on the pattern of missingness.

Research Question

Research Objective

HYPOTHESES

H0: Independent variables do not significantly affect CPI.

H1: At least one independent variable significantly affects CPI.

Model

Model: Multiple Linear Regression (OLS)

Equation:

CPI_t = 0 + 1 Mortgage_t + 2 Unemp_t + 3 NASDAQ_t + 4 Disposable_t + 5 Personal_t + 6 Savings_t + _t

Each beta measures the partial effect of the corresponding regressor on CPI, holding other factors constant. OLS provides unbiased estimates under standard assumptions (exogeneity, no perfect multicollinearity, homoskedasticity, and uncorrelated errors).

Interpretation

  • What the matrix shows: Pairwise Pearson correlations quantify linear co-movement between variables from -1 (perfect inverse) to +1 (perfect positive). High absolute values indicate strong linear association but not causation.

  • High correlations observed: disposablePersonal +0.99, CPIdisposable +0.99, CPIPersonal +0.99. These values indicate almost perfect positive co-movement.

    • Interpretation: Correlations this high typically reflect shared long-run trends (nominal income and consumption rising with prices) rather than clean causal effects. When regressors and the dependent variable are trending, correlations can be large even if no causal link exists.

    • Modeling consequence: Including two predictors with correlation 0.99 will inflate standard errors and produce unstable coefficient estimates (multicollinearity). Use variable selection (drop one), combine via PCA into a single index, or report results from a reduced model to get more reliable inference.

  • Other notable correlations: CPIMortgage strongly negative in your table; this could reflect monetary policy reactions (rates fall when inflation expectations or shocks differ) or coincident trends investigate with time-series methods and by checking contemporaneous vs lagged relationships.

  • Further diagnostics: Compute partial correlations to control for third-variable effects, and run VIFs to quantify inflation of coefficient variance. If variables are cointegrated, pairwise correlation is insufficient run cointegration tests and consider an error-correction framework.

  • Very strong positive correlation between disposable and Personal (~0.99) this signals severe multicollinearity.

  • CPI correlates highly with disposable and Personal, and strongly with NASDAQ potential predictors of CPI movement.

  • Negative correlation between Mortgage and CPI suggests higher mortgage rates are associated with lower CPI in the sample.

Interpretation

  • Purpose: Histograms reveal skewness, modality, and outliers for each variable essential for diagnosing whether transformations are necessary before linear modeling.

  • Observed shapes (detailed):

    • NASDAQ: pronounced right skew and heavy-tailed this reflects episodic market booms (dot-com, 2010s tech surge) producing extreme positive outliers. Mean is pulled upward by large spikes; median is a better central measure for this series.
    • disposable and Personal: both show right skew in levels due to long-term growth; their distributions overlap heavily (consistent with very high correlation). Using levels conflates trend with distributional shape.
    • CPI: distribution in levels is stretched by the long-term trend; the recent uptick around 20202022 adds a heavier right tail relative to earlier decades.

  • Implications for modeling:

    • For heavily skewed variables (NASDAQ), transform to log or use percentage returns to reduce skew and stabilize variance.
    • For trend-dominated variables (disposable, Personal, CPI), use growth rates or detrending to isolate cyclical/co-movement relationships.
    • Outliers: Consider winsorization or robust regression if extreme points unduly influence fits.

  • Statistical considerations: Non-normal univariate distributions suggest residuals might also be non-normal. Use robust or bootstrap inference when sample-based normality assumptions are suspect.

  • Visualization tip: Show kernel density estimates or QQ-plots alongside histograms to better assess normality and tail behavior.

  • NASDAQ, disposable, and Personal are right-skewed with long tails; consider log transforms to reduce skew.

  • personal_savings and Mortgage show relatively concentrated distributions.

Key Observation: Persistent Long-Run Inflation

Stationarity Concerns: Because the mean and variance change over time, the series is non-stationary. To avoid "spurious correlation" in modeling, we must analyse the inflation rate (percentage change) rather than raw price levels.

The 2020 Hockey Stick & Structural Break

The Pandemic Shift: A sharp, near-vertical acceleration begins in 2020, driven by global supply chain disruptions and post-lockdown demand surges.

Modelling Impact: This is a structural break in the data. Historical averages from the 1990s or 2000s are no longer sufficient for forecasting; models must now account for this higher-volatility regime.

Notable Shocks & Volatilities

The 2008 Deflationary Notch: A rare, visible dip occurs during the Global Financial Crisis, marking one of the few periods of actual price contraction.

The Great Moderation (19902015): Most of the timeline shows a predictable, steady slope, which contrasts sharply with the high-velocity growth seen in the final two years of the chart.

MULTIPLE LINEAR REGRESSION

In[59]:
# Prepare dependent and independent variables for regression
y = df['CPI'].dropna()  # dependent variable
X = df[['Mortgage','Unemp_ra','NASDAQ','disposable','Personal','personal_savings']].loc[y.index].astype(float)  # independent vars
X = sm.add_constant(X)  # add intercept term

# Fit OLS regression using statsmodels
model = sm.OLS(y, X, missing='drop')  # use 'drop' to handle any missing rows
results = model.fit()  # fit the model

# Print summary output for interpretation
print(results.summary())

# Save residuals for diagnostics
residuals = results.resid

# Durbin-Watson statistic for autocorrelation
dw_stat = durbin_watson(residuals)

# Breusch-Pagan test for heteroskedasticity
bp_test = het_breuschpagan(residuals, results.model.exog)
bp_output = {'Lagrange multiplier statistic': bp_test[0], 'p-value': bp_test[1], 'f-value': bp_test[2], 'f p-value': bp_test[3]}

# Jarque-Bera test for normality of residuals
jb_stat, jb_pvalue = stats.jarque_bera(residuals)

# Display diagnostics succinctly
diagnostics = {'Durbin-Watson': dw_stat, 'Breusch-Pagan': bp_output, 'Jarque-Bera': {'JB stat': jb_stat, 'p-value': jb_pvalue}}

Interpretation

Income Effects: Positive coefficients on Income variables (Disposable/Personal) confirm "Demand-Pull" inflation; as household wealth rises, the CPI index scales upward.

Contractionary Factors: Negative coefficients for Interest Rates and Savings indicate cooling effects. Higher borrowing costs and increased savings pull liquidity out of the market, slowing CPI growth.

Unit Scale: Each coefficient represents the absolute change in the CPI index for a one-unit change in the predictor (e.g., a $1 change in income or a 1% change in rates).

The R-square Illusion: While an R-square of approximately 0.99 suggests a perfect fit, it is likely spurious because CPI and predictors both trend upward over time.

Autocorrelation Warning: A low Durbin-Watson score indicates that residuals are not independent. This means standard p-values are unreliable and likely overstate the significance of the variables.

Heteroskedasticity: Significant test results (e.g., the Breusch-Pagan test) suggest that the error variance is not constant, requiring Newey-West (HAC) standard errors for valid inference.

DIAGNOSTIC TESTS

Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) Multicollinearity

VIF measures how much the variance of an estimated coefficient increases because of collinearity. Rule-of-thumb: VIF > 10 indicates high multicollinearity.

In[]:
# Prepare independent variables for VIF calculation
X_vif = df[['Mortgage','Unemp_ra','NASDAQ','disposable','Personal','personal_savings']].dropna().astype(float)
X_vif_const = sm.add_constant(X_vif)  # add intercept for VIF computation
vif_df = pd.DataFrame()
vif_df['variable'] = X_vif_const.columns
vif_df['VIF'] = [variance_inflation_factor(X_vif_const.values, i) for i in range(X_vif_const.shape[1])]

Actionable rule-of-thumb

  • VIF > 10: high multicollinearity coefficients may be unstable.
  • Options: drop one of the collinear variables, combine via PCA, or use regularization (Ridge/Lasso).

Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) Test Stationarity

ADF tests the null hypothesis that a series has a unit root (non-stationary). Stationarity is important for valid inference in time-series regressions.

In[51]:
# ADF test for CPI
cpi_series = df['CPI'].dropna()
adf_res = adfuller(cpi_series, autolag='AIC')

We forecast CPI for five future periods using the fitted model. For transparency we assume predictors remain at their last observed values a baseline approach. We discuss limitations of this assumption.

Forecast Expanded Interpretation & Limitations

  • Method used: Baseline hold-last-value forecast: the model predicts future CPI using the most recent observed values of predictors held constant.

  • Why this is limited: Macro predictors (income, consumption, market indices, rates) evolve over time. Holding them constant ignores future dynamics and respondents to shocks, so forecasts are likely biased and understate uncertainty.

  • Uncertainty & model misspecification: Given serial correlation, heteroskedasticity, and potentially non-stationary regressors, the forecast intervals produced under OLS assumptions are too narrow. Model misspecification also increases forecast error in out-of-sample periods, especially across structural breaks (e.g., 2020).

  • Better alternatives:

    • Model CPI growth (CPI) with ARIMA/SARIMA for direct forecasting of inflation rates.
    • Estimate a VAR on stationary transforms of predictors for joint dynamics and impulse-response analysis.
    • If variables are cointegrated, use a VECM to capture long-run equilibrium relations and short-run dynamics.
    • Use rolling-origin cross-validation and ensemble methods to assess forecast stability.

  • Practical recommendation: Treat the baseline forecast as illustrative only. If you want, I can build a VAR on year-over-year percent changes and produce multi-step forecasts with fan charts and impulse-response functions; which forecasting approach would you like me to implement next?

Diagnostics Expanded Interpretation (VIF, DW, BP, JB, ADF)

  • VIF (Variance Inflation Factor):

    • Interpretation: VIF quantifies how much a coefficient's variance is inflated due to multicollinearity among regressors. A rule of thumb: VIF > 510 signals problematic multicollinearity.
    • What we see: disposable (VIF 12.5) indicates severe collinearity. This explains unstable coefficients in the full model and large standard errors for affected variables.
    • Action: Drop or combine collinear predictors, or use regularization for prediction tasks.

  • DurbinWatson (DW):

    • Interpretation: DW 2 indicates no autocorrelation; values << 2 indicate positive autocorrelation in residuals.
    • What we see: DW 0.120.13 indicates strong positive serial correlation. This invalidates OLS standard errors and hypothesis tests.
    • Action: Use HAC (NeweyWest) standard errors or model the residual process explicitly (AR errors), or estimate dynamic models (ARIMA/VAR).

  • BreuschPagan (BP) Heteroskedasticity test:

    • Interpretation: Small p-value rejects homoskedasticity; residual variance depends on fitted values or predictors.
    • Action: Use heteroskedasticity-robust standard errors (HC0HC3) for cross-sectional robustness, or HAC for time-series dependence.

  • JarqueBera (JB) Normality of residuals:

    • Interpretation: Small p-value indicates residuals deviate from normality (skewness/kurtosis issues). In large samples, CLT helps, but small-sample inference may be unreliable.
    • Action: Use bootstrap CIs for coefficients if normality is a concern.

  • ADF (Augmented DickeyFuller) Stationarity test:

    • Interpretation: Failure to reject the unit-root null means the series is non-stationary. Non-stationary regressions can be spurious unless variables are cointegrated.
    • What to do: Test key series (CPI, disposable, Personal) for unit roots; if I(1), then either difference them for short-run analysis or test for cointegration and use an ECM for long-run relationships.

  • Combined diagnostic conclusion: The model suffers from multiple violations of OLS assumptions: multicollinearity, serial correlation, heteroskedasticity, and non-normal residuals. These issues advise caution: do not rely on naive OLS p-values for inference in this dataset. Prefer robust/HAC standard errors, transformations to stationarity, cointegration tests, and dynamic multivariate time-series models.

Forecast Interpretation

Important notes

  • This baseline forecast holds predictors constant use with caution.
  • For realistic scenarios, first model predictors (ARIMA/VAR), then simulate CPI paths.

Policy implications

  • Monetary policy: higher mortgage rates are associated with lower CPI, indicating a housing-finance channel for inflation control.
  • Fiscal and income policy: increases in disposable income and strong equity-market performance are associated with upward pressure on CPI; fiscal stimulus may therefore raise inflationary pressures.
  • Household behaviour: higher personal savings are associated with lower CPI, suggesting that policies encouraging saving can reduce short-term demand-driven inflation.

Limitations

  • OLS assumes exogeneity; potential endogeneity between income measures and CPI is not addressed here and may bias coefficients.
  • The forecasting approach used a baseline assumption (predictors held constant at the last observed values); more realistic forecasts require modelling predictor dynamics (ARIMA/VAR).

Recommendations for future research

  • Estimate vector autoregressions (VAR/VECM) and test for cointegration among CPI, income, and financial variables.
  • Use instrumental variables or structural identification to address endogeneity concerns where appropriate.
  • Apply dimensionality reduction (PCA) or regularization (Ridge/Lasso) to handle multicollinearity and compare coefficient stability.

CONCLUSION

Key findings

  • The reduced OLS model (excluding Personal) explains approximately 99.03% of the variation in CPI (Adj. R = 0.9903) and yields stable coefficient estimates.
  • Statistically significant determinants (p < 0.01) include: Mortgage (negative partial effect), Unemp_ra (positive partial effect), NASDAQ (positive), disposable (positive), and personal_savings (negative).
  • The full model suffers from severe multicollinearity between disposable and Personal (VIFs > 100). Dropping Personal reduces multicollinearity substantially (e.g., disposable VIF 12.48).

The reduced multiple regression offers clear descriptive evidence on CPI determinants. However, policy inference should be supported by additional robustness checks, time-series modelling, and causal identification before drawing definitive conclusions.
